                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d213">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102 Tientsin/245: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dooman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-06-10T15:00:00+09:00"
                            >June 10, 1939—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 11—8:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>267. Department’s 156, June 8, 3 p.m. I spoke today to the Vice Minister for
                    Foreign Affairs<note n="63" xml:id="d213fn63">Renzo Sawada.</note> along the
                    lines desired by the Department. Sawada expressed regret that the attitude
                    reflected by the British officials in Tientsin “left no room” for conciliatory
                    discussions with them by the Japanese. He added however that Caldwell enjoyed
                    the confidence of both sides and that “it would be helpful if he could use his
                    good offices.”</p>
                <p>Repeated to Chungking, Tientsin, Shanghai.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dooman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
